x and y indicate how sensitive the rate is to the change in concentration of A and B.", "fibs": ["Reaction"]}
{"text": "Sum of these exponents, i.e., x + y in (4.4) gives the overall order of a reaction whereas x and y represent the order with respect to the reactants A and B respectively.", "fibs": ["x"]}
{"text": "Hence, the sum of powers of the concentration of the reactants in the rate law expression is called the order of that chemical reaction.", "fibs": ["sum"]}
{"text": "Order of a reaction can be 0, 1, 2, 3 and even a fraction.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "A zero order reaction means that the rate of reaction is independent of the concentration of reactants.", "fibs": ["order"]}
