{"text": "A balanced chemical equation never gives us a true picture of how a reaction takes place since rarely a reaction gets completed in one step.", "fibs": ["chemical"]}
{"text": "The reactions taking place in one step are called elementary reactions.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "When a sequence of elementary reactions (called mechanism) gives us the products, the reactions are called complex reactions.", "fibs": ["sequence"]}
{"text": "These may be consecutive reactions (e.g., oxidation of ethane to CO2 and H2O passes through a series of intermediate steps in which alcohol, aldehyde and acid are formed), reverse reactions and side reactions (e.g., nitration of phenol yields o-nitrophenol and p-nitrophenol).", "fibs": ["oxidation"]}
