{"text": "Summary
Chemical kinetics is the study of chemical reactions with respect to reaction rates, effect of various variables, rearrangement of atoms and formation of intermediates.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "The rate of a reaction is concerned with decrease in concentration of reactants or increase in the concentration of products per unit time.", "fibs": ["rate"]}
{"text": "It can be expressed as instantaneous rate at a particular instant of time and average rate over a large interval of time.", "fibs": ["rate"]}
{"text": "A number of factors such as temperature, concentration of reactants, catalyst, affect the rate of a reaction.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Mathematical representation of rate of a reaction is given by rate law.", "fibs": ["representation"]}
{"text": "Order of a reaction with respect to a reactant is the power of its concentration which appears in the rate law equation.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "The order of a reaction is the sum of all such powers of concentration of terms for different reactants.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Rate constant is the proportionality factor in the rate law.", "fibs": ["proportionality"]}
{"text": "Rate constant and order of a reaction can be determined from rate law or its integrated rate equation.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Molecularity is defined only for an elementary reaction.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "Its values are limited from 1 to 3 whereas order can be 0, 1, 2, 3 or even a fraction.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Molecularity and order of an elementary reaction are same.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Temperature dependence of rate constants is described by Arrhenius equation (k = Ae–Ea/RT).", "fibs": ["Temperature"]}
{"text": "Ea corresponds to the activation energy and is given by the energy difference between activated complex and the reactant molecules, and A (Arrhenius factor or pre-exponential factor) corresponds to the collision frequency.", "fibs": ["activation"]}
{"text": "The equation clearly shows that increase of temperature or lowering of Ea will lead to an increase in the rate of reaction and presence of a catalyst lowers the activation energy by providing an alternate path for the reaction.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "According to collision theory, another factor P called steric factor which refers to the orientation of molecules which collide, is important and contributes to effective collisions, thus, modifying the Arrhenius equation to .", "fibs": ["collision"]}
